\section*{Problem Statement}
A car accelerates from 0 to 50 mph in 5 seconds. Calculate its acceleration in m/s². If it maintains this acceleration, how fast will it be going in 10 seconds?

\section*{Solution}

\subsection*{Step 1: Convert mph to m/s}
We know:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Initial speed, \(v_i = 0 \, \text{mph}\)
    \item Final speed, \(v_f = 50 \, \text{mph}\)
\end{itemize}

To convert 50 mph to meters per second:

\[
1 \text{ mile} = 1609.34 \text{ meters, and } 1 \text{ hour} = 3600 \text{ seconds.}
\]

\[
v_f = 50 \times \frac{1609.34}{3600} \approx 22.35 \, \text{m/s.}
\]

\subsection*{Step 2: Calculate acceleration}
The formula for acceleration is:

\[
a = \frac{v_f - v_i}{t}.
\]

\[
a = \frac{22.35 - 0}{5} = 4.47 \, \text{m/s².}
\]

\subsection*{Step 3: Speed after 10 seconds}
To calculate the speed after 10 seconds if the acceleration remains constant:

\[
v = v_i + at.
\]

\[
v = 0 + 4.47 \times 10 = 44.7 \, \text{m/s.}
\]

\subsection*{Final Answers}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Acceleration:} \(4.47 \, \text{m/s²}\)
    \item \textbf{Speed after 10 seconds:} \(44.7 \, \text{m/s}\), which is approximately \(100 \, \text{mph.}\)
\end{itemize}

